attributes.summary: The device identifier that produced this input.
The current state of this input. Input objects exist for the full lifecycle of the input (Begin, Change..., End)
If the input was generated by a keyboard or mouse, this represents which key or mouse button was responsible.
The type of input that generated this event.
The position of the input. For mouse inputs, this is the cursor position. For touch inputs, this is the position of the touch and Z represents the touch pressure if hardware allows.

The change in position since the last state change. For mouse inputs, this is the change in cursor position (even if the cursor is locked). For scroll wheel events, the Z component represents the amount scrolled.
Sets focus to the given input focusable instance.
Clears focus from the current input focusable instance.
Returns true if the given key is currently held down, false otherwise.
Fires when an input begins.
Fires when an input changes.
Fires when an input ends.
Fires when text is entered.
An internal universally unique identifier for the instance.
Determines if the instance can be stored in a level file.
The name of the instance, not necessarily unique.
The parent of the instance in the tree structure.
The children of the instance in the tree structure.

Returns a string representing the instance's location in the hierarchy, using '.' to separate names. If RelativeTo is provided, the path will be relative to that instance. If RelativeTo is not an ancestor of this instance, the full path will be returned.
Returns true if this instance is a descendant of the other instance, false otherwise.
Returns true if this instance is an ancestor of the other instance, false otherwise.
Returns true if this instance is of the given class or a subclass of it, false otherwise.
Returns all descendants of this instance.
Used internally for network replication of property changes.
Fires when a property is changed.
Fires when a child is added to the instance in the tree structure. The instance will already be in its parent's Children table when this is fired.
Fires when a child is removed from the instance in the tree structure. The instance will no longer be in its parent's Children table when this is fired.

Fires when any descendant of this instance is added, and receives both the new descendant and its immediate parent. The immediate parent can be this instance. Fires immediately after ChildAdded is fired on the immediate parent.

Fires when any descendant of this instance is removed, and receives both the removed descendant and its former immediate parent. The immediate parent can be this instance. Fires immediately after ChildRemoved is fired on the immediate parent.
The object's world transform.
The primary axis of the attachment. This corresponds to the right vector of the attachment's transform.
The secondary axis of the attachment. This corresponds to the up vector of the attachment's transform.
The world transform of the attachment.
The primary axis of the attachment. This corresponds to the right vector of the attachment's transform.
The secondary axis of the attachment. This corresponds to the up vector of the attachment's transform.
The world transform of the attachment.
The size of the box collider.
The rigid body that this collider is attached to. Determined automatically.
The body's physical properties.
The field of view of the camera in degrees.
The near clipping plane distance.
The far clipping plane distance.
Determines if the UI element and its descendants are visible. Non-visible UI elements do not receive input events.

Determines if the UI element and its descendants can receive input events. If false, the UI element will not receive input events, but its children may still receive input events if they have Active set to true.
Determines if the UI element can be selected. If false, the UI element will not be selectable, but its children may still be selectable if they have Selectable set to true.

Determines if the UI element is currently selected. Only one UI element can be selected at a time. Setting this to true will automatically set all other selectable UI elements' Selected property to false.
Determines if the UI element can be focused. If false, the UI element will not be focusable, but its children may still be focusable if they have Focusable set to true.

Determines if the UI element is currently focused. Only one UI element can be focused at a time. Setting this to true will automatically set all other focusable UI elements' Focused property to false.
Determines the background color and opacity of the UI frame.
The absolute size in pixels of the layer.
